{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512191"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:51:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:51:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11857"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11857","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11857"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0.02,0.88,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4457"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11857"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2551"},{"type":"tags","id":"5591"},{"type":"tags","id":"5967"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6462"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12444"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33790"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old, otherwise well man is being reviewed in the recovery area having just undergone a total knee replacement due to severe osteoarthritis. Prior to the procedure he was incredibly anxious and was given 4mg of midazolam intravenously. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe procedure was performed under a general anaesthetic, with a standard induction using propofol, fentanyl and rocuronium. The patient become hypotensive and transiently desaturated to an SpO2 of 60% during induction. The procedure itself was prolonged and technically difficult from a surgical standpoint, requiring re-paralysis and multiple doses of analgesia (fentanyl, oxycodone, paracetamol and celecoxib) intraoperatively to maintain anaesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEventually the procedure was completed without complication. It was determined by the anaesthetist that the patient required a morphine PCA due to concerns about the risk of post-operative pain. In recovery, a review is requested for the patient as he is drowsy and difficult to rouse with a respiratory rate of 6/min.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Administration of which one of the following would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metaraminol","Flumazenil","N-acetylcysteine","Naloxone","Sugammadex"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOpioids are commonly used in the management of intra-operative and postoperative pain. Opioid toxicity initially causes rising sedation levels, confusion and euphoria. At this stage, reducing dosage or delaying the next required dose is often enough to alleviate the problem. If not promptly recognised, opioid overdose will result in respiratory depression followed by a decrease in oxygen saturation. Oxygen saturation changes may not be evident in the early stages especially if the patient is on supplementary oxygen. Additional clinical manifestations of opioid toxicity include miosis, constipation, nausea and vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of suspected opioid overdose should follow the advanced life support algorithm to secure the airway and support breathing and circulation as required. The antidote to opioid overdose is \u003Cstrong\u003Enaloxone\u003C/strong\u003E, which is administered intravenously in 0.04-0.2 mg doses every 2-3 minutes, titrated to clinical effect up to a maximum initial dose of 10 mg. It is important to note that the half-life of naloxone is less than one hour in comparison to the half-life of morphine which is approximately three hours. Thus, repeated doses or an infusion may be required to maintain clinical effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPost-operative benzodiazepine overdose is less likely in this case, as midazolam is a short acting benzodiazepine and was administered before the start of the case. If benzodiazepine overdose is suspected and requires immediate reversal, \u003Cstrong\u003Eflumazenil\u003C/strong\u003E 0.1-0.2 mg IV boluses can be given every minute until reversal to a maximum dose of 2 mg. It is worth noting that this reversal agent carries a risk of precipitating seizures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-acetylcysteine\u003C/strong\u003E can be administered as an antidote to paracetamol overdose and acts by increasing the synthesis and availability of glutathione and by directly binding to NAPQI (the toxic compound produced by paracetamol breakdown). Paracetamol toxicity would not cause the symptoms described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetaraminol \u003C/strong\u003Eis a vasopressor used for the treatment of hypotension in critical care. Whilst hypotension is a common side effect of many anaesthetic agents, it is unlikely to be the cause of this post-operative presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESugammadex \u003C/strong\u003Eis a drug used in anaesthetics for the reversal of steroidal non-depolarising muscle relaxants rocuronium and vecuronium. Whilst residual paralysis is an important differential in the post operative patient with poor respiratory effort, this would not cause drowsiness and sedation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Opioid overdose can result in severe respiratory depression and potentially death if not recognised early","The antidote to opioid toxicity is naloxone intravenously in 0.04-0.2 mg doses every 2-3 minutes, titrated to clinical effect up to a maximum initial dose of 10 mg"],"references":["Boyer EW. Management of opioid analgesic overdose. N Engl J Med. 2012 Jul 12;367(2):146-55. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra1202561. PMID: 22784117; PMCID: PMC3739053. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMra1202561","Toxicology. In: Therapeutic guidelines [online]. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11857"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T11:50:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T11:52:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4457"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101501"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr